      <h1>B2B Lead Generation: What It Is and How It Works</h1>

      <p><strong>B2B lead generation</strong> — business-to-business lead generation — is the process a company uses to attract individuals at other businesses who might buy its products or services, and then capture enough information about them to hand off to a sales team for follow-up.</p>

      <div class="verdict-box">
        <p><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Three structural shifts have made B2B lead generation both more important and more complex. Buyers are now 61% through their decision-making process before contacting a supplier. 67% of the buying journey occurs online. And the lead generation industry is projected to reach $295 billion by 2027. Getting the process right is not optional — it is the primary revenue engine for most B2B organizations.</p>
      </div>

      <p>A "lead" is a potential buyer who has taken some measurable action: filling out a form, downloading a whitepaper, signing up for a webinar, or responding to an outbound email. This is distinct from a passive website visitor — they have raised their hand in some way. Most B2B organisations classify leads through a progression: MQL (Marketing-Qualified Lead), SQL (Sales-Qualified Lead), and PQL (Product-Qualified Lead for SaaS models).</p>

      <div class="methodology">
        <p><strong>Who wrote this:</strong> This article was prepared by an editorial research team that evaluates online business, marketing, and sales strategies based on publicly available data and practitioner research.</p>
        <p><strong>How this guide was built:</strong> This article draws on publicly available research from B2B marketing analytics firms, industry benchmark reports, and practitioner-oriented publications. Statistics cited trace to their primary sources and are linked directly. Data reviewed June 2026.</p>
      </div>
