    <section id="process">
      <h2>The Six-Stage B2B Lead Generation Process</h2>

      <p>B2B lead generation is not a single tactic — it is a six-stage process that moves a potential buyer from anonymous interest to a qualified sales conversation. Most B2B teams underperform not because they lack tactics at any single stage, but because the stages are disconnected: leads attracted well are captured poorly, or captured well and never nurtured.</p>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Define the ICP (Ideal Customer Profile).</strong> Before any tactic: who is the target? Which industry, company size, role, budget range, and geography describes the buyer who gets the most value from what you sell? Every tactic downstream flows from this definition.</li>
        <li><strong>Attract.</strong> Drive traffic from potential buyers using the channels best suited to your ICP: organic content and SEO for long-cycle buyers doing independent research; LinkedIn for mid-to-senior roles; paid search for solution-aware queries; webinars for buyers who want to evaluate expertise before committing.</li>
        <li><strong>Capture.</strong> Convert anonymous visitors into identified contacts via landing pages, lead magnets, or LinkedIn Lead Gen Forms. The offer must be specific enough to attract the right contacts and not just anyone looking for free content.</li>
        <li><strong>Qualify.</strong> Lead scoring assigns points based on demographic fit (company size, industry, role) and behavioural signals (pages visited, content downloaded, email engagement). Only contacts above the scoring threshold pass to sales as MQLs.</li>
        <li><strong>Nurture.</strong> 79% of marketing leads never convert to sales, with inadequate nurturing cited as the primary cause. Nurture means staying relevant — sending useful content over weeks or months until the lead signals readiness to talk.</li>
        <li><strong>Convert (hand off to sales).</strong> When a lead crosses the SQL threshold, they move to sales for direct outreach. Speed matters: leads followed up within 5 minutes are 9x more likely to convert than those contacted after 30 minutes.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>The average B2B sales cycle runs approximately 10.1 months, compared to minutes or hours for most B2C purchases. The process demands patience and a higher content investment per contact, but the value of each closed customer is typically orders of magnitude higher than a single B2C transaction.</p>

