    <section id="channels">
      <h2>Which Channels Produce the Best B2B Leads?</h2>

      <p>There is no universally best channel — the right choice depends on your ICP, deal size, and content capability. What the data shows clearly is that cost per lead and lead quality vary dramatically by channel.</p>

      <div class="table-scroll">
      <table>
        <tr><th>Channel</th><th>Avg CPL</th><th>Key Data Point</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Organic SEO / Content</td><td>$31</td><td>SEO leads close at 14.6% vs. 1.7% for outbound (Search Engine Journal)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Email marketing</td><td>$53</td><td>42% of companies cite email as most important lead channel (DemandSage)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Webinars</td><td>$72</td><td>73% say webinars produce best-quality leads (Cvent)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>LinkedIn</td><td>$75</td><td>Drives ~80% of B2B social leads (HubSpot)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Paid search (PPC)</td><td>$110</td><td>High intent; faster than organic but higher CPL</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Events / Trade shows</td><td>$811–$881</td><td>Highest CPL; best for enterprise relationship-building</td></tr>
      </table>
      </div>

      <p>The data supports a clear efficiency hierarchy: SEO and content are the cheapest channels per lead with the highest close rates over time. LinkedIn and email add direct outreach capability. Webinars add a qualification layer. Events are expensive per lead but sometimes irreplaceable for enterprise deals.</p>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>Channel insight:</strong> 89% of B2B marketers use LinkedIn for lead generation, and it drives approximately 80% of all B2B social media leads. LinkedIn is 277% more effective for B2B lead generation than Facebook or other social platforms (LinkedIn B2B Institute).
      </div>

      <p>For affiliate marketers exploring B2B list-building strategies, organic content and email nurture form the backbone of a sustainable lead generation system that does not depend on any single platform's advertising algorithm.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="performance">
      <h2>What the Numbers Say About B2B Lead Generation Performance</h2>

      <p>The headline metrics in B2B lead generation reveal a consistent pattern: most businesses generate enough leads — they convert too few of them, and they nurture almost none of them effectively.</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>79% of marketing leads never convert to sales.</strong> The primary cause is inadequate lead nurturing — contacts are captured and then ignored until they go cold (<a href="https://www.marketingsherpa.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MarketingSherpa, 2023</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Only 27% of B2B leads generated by marketing are ever contacted by sales.</strong> Nearly three-quarters of captured leads receive zero follow-up (<a href="https://www.salesforce.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Salesforce, 2024</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Companies excelling at lead nurturing generate 50% more sales-ready leads at 33% lower cost</strong> — a compound advantage that builds over time (99Firms).</li>
        <li><strong>Companies with mature lead management processes report 133% more revenue</strong> than those with immature processes (<a href="https://www.forrester.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Forrester, 2023</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>B2B organizations that align sales and marketing achieve 24% faster revenue growth</strong> and 27% faster profit growth (Forrester, 2023).</li>
        <li><strong>ABM programs see a 70% increase in pipeline value per targeted account</strong> (<a href="https://www.demandbase.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Demandbase, 2024</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Average B2B website conversion rate: 2.23%</strong> — roughly 98 in 100 visitors leave without providing contact details (Power Digital).</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout warn">
        <strong>The gap that matters most:</strong> The difference between a team generating leads and one generating revenue is almost always nurturing. A system that captures 100 leads and nurtures 80 of them outperforms one that captures 300 leads and nurtures none.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="mistakes">
      <h2>Common B2B Lead Generation Mistakes</h2>

      <p>The same failure patterns appear repeatedly across B2B lead generation programmes, regardless of company size or industry.</p>

      <h3>1. Chasing Volume Instead of Quality</h3>
      <p>61% of B2B marketers identify lead quality — not quantity — as their biggest challenge (HubSpot / DemandSage). Yet most teams measure success by leads generated per month, not by leads that eventually close.</p>

      <h3>2. No Nurturing System</h3>
      <p>The 79% non-conversion statistic points directly here. Most teams have a capture mechanism but no systematic nurture sequence to engage contacts between capture and purchase readiness.</p>

      <h3>3. Slow or No Follow-Up</h3>
      <p>Responding within 5 minutes of a high-intent action increases conversion probability by 9x. Yet 42% of sales reps report being too busy to follow up that quickly (InBeat Agency).</p>

      <h3>4. Single-Channel Dependency</h3>
      <p>Relying on one channel — most commonly LinkedIn outbound or cold email alone — creates pipeline fragility. When that channel's performance drops, the entire pipeline stalls.</p>

      <h3>5. Sales and Marketing Misalignment</h3>
      <p>Only 41% of marketers report being satisfied with their multi-channel lead generation strategy (Salesforce). Misaligned definitions of what constitutes a qualified lead cause much of this friction.</p>
