      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between a lead and a prospect in B2B?</summary>
        <p>A lead is anyone who has shown initial interest and provided contact details. A prospect is a lead that has been qualified: they match your target company size, industry, budget range, and decision-making authority. Not every lead becomes a prospect, which is why lead scoring is central to B2B lead generation.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between an MQL and an SQL?</summary>
        <p>An MQL (Marketing-Qualified Lead) is a contact who has engaged with your marketing content enough to suggest buying intent. An SQL (Sales-Qualified Lead) is a contact that the sales team has reviewed and confirmed as a real opportunity. Only 12–18% of MQLs become SQLs (MarketJoy).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Which channels drive the highest-quality B2B leads?</summary>
        <p>73% of B2B marketers say webinars produce their best-quality leads (Cvent). LinkedIn drives ~80% of B2B social leads (LinkedIn B2B Institute). Organic search delivers leads that close at 14.6% — roughly 8.6x the close rate of outbound leads (Search Engine Journal).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a good B2B lead conversion rate?</summary>
        <p>A conversion rate of 2–5% is generally considered good. The average B2B website converts at approximately 2.23% (Power Digital). Legal services leads all sectors at 7.4%, while B2B e-commerce converts at around 1.8%.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How much does B2B lead generation cost?</summary>
        <p>Cost per lead varies significantly by channel. Organic SEO averages $31, email $53, webinars $72, LinkedIn advertising $75, paid search $110, and trade shows $811–$881 (DemandSage). The median B2B CPL across all channels sits at approximately $198–$214.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is Account-Based Marketing (ABM)?</summary>
        <p>ABM is a targeted B2B strategy where sales and marketing align around a defined list of high-value accounts rather than casting a wide net. Demandbase data shows ABM programs see a 70% increase in pipeline value per targeted account. It is most effective for high average contract values.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is AI changing B2B lead generation?</summary>
        <p>AI has moved into active qualification and routing. AI agents autonomously handle prospect research, data enrichment, lead scoring, and real-time routing. Forrester reports AI-powered lead scoring improves conversion rates by approximately 30%. Businesses using AI report 50% more sales-ready leads and 60% lower customer acquisition costs.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

